<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99188165626542></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99188165626542><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=99188165626542>Barbarian Shaman Guide.</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=99188165626542#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Jun 6th 10:40 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>This is my guide for begining Barbarian Shamans. I have gotten 6 different classes to between levels 10 and 15. Though this does not make me an expert, and certenly does not give me any insite into the high level game, I think it qualifies me to help newbies through the early levels. Note this is for True Newbies, though others who have never played a Barbarian Shaman my benifit from it as well. If you don't like my conclusions or suggestions say so, but don't flame, please be civil. Also this is a first, rough draft, so feel free to point out the many spelling or gramar mistakes if you wish, and any flaws you see in my logic.<br><br><br><br>Before Character Creation:<br><br>Go to <a href="http://www.eqatlas.com/" target=_new>http://www.eqatlas.com/</a> and download and print the maps for everfrost and blackburrow. Also go to <a href="http://eq.castersrealm.com/" target=_new>http://eq.castersrealm.com/</a> and become familiar with what your spells are and what they do, and how much they cost. The maps will be a life saver to you. Blackburrow and Everfrost are very confusing Zones, Everfrost in particular as everything looks the same in the canyons. If you get lost after 4th level just gate home.<br><br><br><br>Character Creation:<br><br>Barbarian shamans have a bit of flexibulity in applying their stat points. I would reccomend putting 25 points into Wisdom, because frankly WIS is very important to a shaman, not only for mana but also for skill increases. However you *could* put 20 or less there, I just wouldn't reccomend it. That leaves you with 5 points. Casters Realm, and most other creation guides reccomend you put your remaining points in to AGL, higher agility means you avoid attacks a little better, which is important, but I think there are a few other things to think about. A shaman can wear heavy armor and will melee occasionaly, especialy at earlyer levels, so a point or two in STR couldn't hurt. DEX also helps you land blows, and learn this skill as you use it, so bringing it up to 75 is not totaly uncalled for. I personaly put 25 points in WIS, 2 points in STR, and 3 points in AGL. More becase I like nice round numbers, than any particular goal.<br><br>Should you go Agnostic or Tribunal? It's never been a question for me. The faction with the Tribunal arent too bad, and I like acting like Judge Dredd: Judge, Jury, and Exictioner, dispencing the justice of the tribunal across the land. Have fun with it.<br><br><br>The first 10 minutes:<br><br>Type /book, them memorise your spells. In the examples to follow I will assume you memorised the "minor healing" spell in slot 8 and the "burst of flame" in slot 1.<br><br>Click on the abilities button and set ability 1 (upper left) to sence heading, and ability 2 (upper right) to bind wound. Ability 3 and 4 will probably be fishing and beg.<br><br>Click on combat and set the combat loaction 7 (middle left) to slam.<br><br>Click on the socials button on the right hand side of the window. Flip over to page 2. Make the following macros:<br><br>Help!:<br>/doability 1<br>/yell<br>/g Get it off me, get it off me!<br><br>In a solo situation this will let others around you know you need help. Some will help you, such as myself, others will know to get out of the way. (especialy if you are ingaged with a vengefull.) However in a group setting it allows the others to know you are getting beat up and asks the warrior to taunt it off of you. And the /doability practices sence heading. You never need to conciously practice the skill because all the other macros include it so you paractice it just by doing what you normaly do.<br><br>Meddy:<br>/doability 1<br>/g I am gonna sit down and meditate for a bit. Let me know if I'm needed.<br>/book<br><br>This allows you to meditate, with a hot button and lets your group know whats up.<br><br>SLAM:<br>/doability 1<br>/doability 7<br><br>This allows you to slam and practice your sence heading. You might also want to put the actual slam button in your hot buttons aria so you can see when it pops.<br><br>Train:<br>/doability 1<br>/Shout I'm training %T to the guards.<br><br>or<br><br>Zone:<br>/doability 1<br>/shout I'm training %T to the zone line.<br><br>Others you may try later when you group more often, are:<br><br>OOM:<br>/doability 1<br>/g I am out of manna. ____OOM____<br><br>Heal:<br>/doability 1<br>/g Healing %T.<br>/cast 8<br><br>Slow:<br>/doability 1<br>/g Slowing %T.<br>/cast # (what ever number you have it set to.)<br><br>Root:<br>/doability 1<br>/g Rooting %T.<br>/cast #<br><br>Poison:<br>/doability 1<br>/g Poisioning %T.<br>/cast #<br><br>You get the idea. These types of hot buttons have two purposes, one is letting your group know what you are doing, so you all can work togeather well. Secondly they allow you to practice your sence heading. Other classes that get more abilities this is even more importent, but knowing which direction you are facing is always nice, especialy in EverFrost.<br><br><br><br>First 30 minutes:<br><br>Turn in your guild note to the guild mistess. She's all the way in the back. She will give you a guild tunic. It's only 2 AC so we will want to upgrade it as soon as possible, but it's a start. Talk to Cindl (in the kilt shop) and say "what mammoth hide parchment?", then got to Greta (near the kilt shop outside) and say "what ink?". Take the stuff they give you and give it to Jinkus in the shaman guild. Take what he gives you and put it in the bank. We will deal with it later. Go to Dok in Dok's Cigars. Ask him about cigars and he will eventualy give you a jar to collect honeycombs in. Give it back to him combined and he will give you an everburn candle. Not a bad light source and give a minor resist to cold attacks. Though you will just be using the jar in your bank for now to hold tiny items. Go to Waltor Felligan outside the shammy guild, tell him "I will assist in gathering fungus", he will give you a jar to collect fungus from wolly spiders in. If you fill it up and combine it, give it back to him and he will give you a 5th level spell, coins, exp, and faction. Go to Lysbith McNatt the warrior guild mistress, and tell her "I will protect the pass" she will give you a 6 slot pack to combine Ice Goblin Necklaces in. Combine it and give it back to her for faction, coins, and exp.<br><br><br><br>On to the fighting:<br><br>Equip your tunic and your club. Time to bonk some heads. Head down the ramp till you get to the monster highway. Polarbear Cubs, Decaying Skelitens, Wooly Spiderlings, Gnoll Pups, Ice Goblin Whelps, and the occasional Vengefull will walk back and forth. Heres the problem, every one of these is hostile to you. Unless they will no longer give you exp when you kill them, they will attack you if you get too close. Don't fight them out in the middle of the highway.<br><br>Stand back a little bit down the canyon twards halas and use your spell "burst of flame" to "pull" creatures to you. Beware, if there is another creature of the same type near it when you hit it, they will both come to you. You could also go right from halas and go in the next canyon down which has an Ice Goblin camp in it and pull from here. It has a wider field of view.<br><br>At first level fight decaying skelitens, at second level either stay fighting decaying skelitens or move up to goblin whelps or gnoll pups. After second level you are a match for just about anything else on a one for one basis except the Vengefulls. I still reccomend you don't start fighting Wooly Spiderlings untill 4th level or so, because though they only do it rarely they can occasionaly turn the tables on you at third.<br><br>Always wach out for the Vengefulls. Vengefull Soloist, Vengefull Lyrisyst, and one other. They look just like a Decaying Skeletin, but are way red to you untill like 9th level or so. However they are weak for their ratings, if you combine the forces of 4 or 5 newbies you could possibly hunt them for good experience. Otherwise run from them if they agro on you, shout that you are training a Vengefull to the guards, this will let everyone know to pull it off of you or to get out of the way.<br><br><br><br>Loot:<br><br>There are a lot of things that will drop off of the monsters in the newbie aria in EverFrost here is what you should do with them.<br><br>Bone Chips: Keep 'em. Put 'em in the bank. As a matter of fact buy any you see in the shops if you can afford them. They will be very usefull later on.<br><br>Ruined Bear Pelts: Sell them at first, but later they can be used to make any armor that Cindl does not give you. Combine one ruined pelt with one pattern in a sewing kit and it should give you a piece of armor if you're lucky or have high enough skill.<br><br>Low Quality Bear Pelts: Combine one of these with a silk thread in a sewing kit to get a leather padding if you are lucky or have a high enough skill.<br><br>Medium Quality Bear Pelts: Just hold on to them for now. Once you get a skinning knife (can be bought for about 5 to 10 pp) combine the knife with the pelt to get a low quality pelt and your knofe back. Then use the LQ pelt as normal.<br><br>High Quality Bear Pelts: There are rare drops but oh-so-nice. If you get one Bank it immidiately. Eventualy you may see someone advertising a need for them. Get 25 to 30 pp for each one miniumum. Otherwise hold on to them and they can be sold later.<br><br>White Polar Bear Pelts: Give them one at a time to Cindl in the kilt shop. She will give you a gold piece and a piece of tattered or patchwork armor. Sometimes she will give you a piece of rawhide instead. Not to mention she gives you a faction bonus.<br><br>Spiderling Silks: Combine 2 of these in a sewing kit to get a silk thread. Keep the thread. Also buy the silk if you find it in the shops, assuming you have the money. This is one of the componants in leather padding.<br><br>Wooly Fungus: Put it in the jar from Waltor. Combine and give it to him when filled.<br><br>Ice Goblin Necklasses: Put in pack from Lysbith untill full. Combine then return to her. Remember to tell her "I will protect the pass" again to get another pack. It's a free 6 slot back pack, great for holding bone chips once you quit brining in necklasses. Like Bone Chips and White Polarbear Skins buy them from shops if you see them.<br><br>Pcaks and Bags: From time to time, gnoll pups and Goblin Whelps. In the begining keep them all, you can't cary much without them, as time goes on keep only the 6 slot large bags and the 8 slot backpacks. Sell the rest.<br><br>Other Junk: Other things such as rusty weapons, gnoll pup scalps, spiderling eyes and legs, will drop from the newbie monsters. Just sell them.<br><br><br><br>Spells:<br><br>You should buy any spells of your own levels you can afford as you can afford them. Don't buy anything above your level yet unless you get lucky and someone buys a HQ bear pelt from you. More on this later. However practice your spell skills as much as possible. This includes summoning food and water even if it is tedious, because it increases your conjuration skill, which is used for your DoT's later. (Damage over Time)<br><br><br>After level 5:<br><br>At this point most of the stuff running around in the newbie zone is green to you, and though it may still give you experience it's not worth it except for the loot. It's time to move on. You could get a partner and camp the Gnoll guards inthe tunnel between Everfrost and Black Burrow.&nbsp;&nbsp;This is a rather slow spawn for two people but can be a little dangerous for a single, however there is a wandering guard there that will help you with gnolls but runs away from Vengefulls, so beware is someone trains one to the zone. Or you could solo or group on the top level of black burrow.<br><br>Regardless of which one you decide to do it's time to go to Quenos. Go through the tunnel to blackburrow, bring a light. You can kill the guards on the way in or just run to the zone, but give a shout that you are training to the zone first. Once in black burrow take a left and find the zone to quenos hills. Once in quenos hills take a left and run to the quenos zone. Inside quenos find the bank, take the wanted poster out and give it to the armored guard there. Take what he gives you and put it back in the bank. After than find Voleen Bakery and tell Karn Tassen "what muffin supply" and he will give you a 10 slot box that will hold small items. Again great for holding bone chips. Put it in the bank. If you want to hunt in blackburrow I would reccomend getting bound in quenos if you can, the death run from halas to blackburrow is a real pain. If you wish to stay bound in halas make shure you have some torches in the bank. If you get bound in quenos then run back to halas and give the list from the bank to Jinkus and he gives you the Initiate Symbol of the Tribunal. If you decided to stay bound in Halas just gate back.<br><br><br><br>Initiate Symbol of the Tribunal:<br><br>LORE ITEM MAGIC ITEM NO DROP<br>AC: +3<br>Wis: +1<br>Mana: +3<br>Deity: The Tribunal<br>Inventory Slot: Neck<br><br>Summons: Hammer of Wrath<br>LORE ITEM MAGIC ITEM NO DROP<br>Damage: 6<br>Delay: 32<br>Skill: 1H Blunt<br><br><br><br>Black Burrow:<br><br>This is a dangerous zone and I died often here. So often infact that I only made it to level 6 before I decided to leave. The experience is good and you can get Patches of Gnoll Fur here, just as long as you can avoid dieing. Why this is so hard is that adds (gnolls that stroll by and decide to help out their friends) will happen about every third Gnoll you fight on the lower levels, even if you are being carefull. Otherwise trains will be flying by almost constantly, so very strong gnolls will be all over the place in large numbers. In a good group this place can be great experience, but at low levels good groups that stay togeather for long just dont seem to be too common. I reccomend hanging around and gaining level 6 here, if after that you feel you can handle the zone stay as long as you like. If you don't feel the zone is for you it's time to leave.<br><br><br><br>Gnoll Fur:<br><br>If you combine 4 patches of gnoll fur in a sewing kit you get a gnoll fur patch. (both stackable) once you combine 4 gnoll fur patches in a kit you get a gnoll fur quarter. Combine four gnoll fur quarters you get a gnoll fur bundle. Gnoll fur bundles are cloaks that can be worn by any class and any race. It gives +4AC and +5 save vs. cold. Nice for low level Int Casters, or you can use it yourself. Otherwise you can give it to Vanna MacGibbons (whom I have not found but is supposed to be in the halas bank.) and she is supposed to give you a magic dagger.<br><br><br><br>After Black Burrow:<br><br>I made the run at level 6, but you could wait untill level 9, so you can do it with Spirit of Wolf, but eather way I reccomend going to Freeport. Before you go, put anything valuable in the bank. To get there go through the zone in quenos hills (left against the wall from blackburrow or right against the wall from quenos). In western karanas hang a right and follow the wall till you hit the water. Follow the water to the left untill you zone. In north karanas continue to follow the water untill you get to the stone bridge. Continue following the water around untill you get to the wooden bridge. (beware you will have to swim around some bandits along the way.) Cross the wooden bridge. In south karanas follow the water to the right and then follow the wall to the left. Eventualy you will come to a big ravene, follow it up, be carefull around the towers as they have bandits in them. Inch around them as far away as you can, but don't fall off the wall and you will be ok. Once you zone in to highpass stay at the zone and see if someone will bind you there. If you get attacked zone back to karanas, wait a minute or two and zone back. Offer to pay a plat or two to make it worth their while and you should get a bind in no time. Make a run through highpass (you have a map right?) and then to Kithcor forest. Kithcor is DANGEROUS, period. Even walking along the left wall is not always safe, because I have seen a Decaying Knoght's Pet right up there on the wall in broad daylight. Just stay to the wall if you can and make a detour around anything hanging out on the wall. Good Luck. Once you follow the wall to the zone line you will be in west commons. In west commons make a run straight ahead from the zone. Keep along the left wall but not up on it there are orc, undead, and dervish camps there. This is a dangerous zone if you have never been here before, but if you are familiar with the zone, you can cross it with a 1st level character with little problem. Once you zone hang a right and head twards the buildings you see there. Near the buildings there will be a trail, follow it to the freeport zone line. Get a bind in freeport.<br><br><br><br>Ok, I'm in freeport, now what?:<br><br>Well you remeber those leather paddings we were making and the HQ bear pelts we were keeping? You can sell them easy in freeport or in east commons. Just send a tell that you have them and wait. Sell HQ bear pelts for 30pp. Sell a full stack of leather padding for 100pp easy. If you want you can sell them for 125pp to 150pp, but it may take a bit to find a buyer. The demand is small but significantly higher than the supply which is also very small. Once you get some cash, about 70pp to 100pp buy some armor. A smith will usualy make you banded armor at a cost of 1pp per AC. Get a full set. Then go buy a shield. I spent about 10pp on mine to get an 8AC shield.<br><br>Alternately you could head over to Kaladim first. Go to east freeport and ride the boat to the other side. Go to Kaladim by staying on the trail. Inside kaladim go to the nort zone and talk to Gunlok. Gunlok is the paladin guildmaster. (remember I said to save them) Give him four stacks of four to speed things up. He will give you Faction, an item, money, and experience. The items won't be usefull to you, so I reccomend selling them. After you give him enough bone chips to start dropping things on the ground, head over to the cleric guild you passed to get to gunloc. Sell in there. The reason is that they will use the faction that you gain from giving the chips to gunloc. It's nice because you get slightly better money for your items. I had 20 stacks of bone chips at 6th level and I got something like 30pp for selling the stuff and I got to level 9.  The cleric merchants not regard me warmly. You may ask why is this important I'll probably never go back here. The answer is simple. They sell some of the spells you need. It's nice to have a merchant that regards you warmly to buy 30pp spells from. I would reccomend using your money from selling items to purchace all the spells you can from from the clerics, then go to greater faydark to buy spells you need from the druid guild in kethlan and the enchanter guild in the high elf city. (They have serpent sight, as a barbarian, you muxst have this spell it makes things SO much easyer.)<br><br><br><br>After Freeport:<br><br>Ok, you have all the spells that you can use at this level, have a full suit of banded armor, and   a shield. Now what?<br><br>Get naked: Put all your armor, money, and stuff in the bank. Cast spirit of the wolf and run back to halas. You need to train in medditate, though this will be the last thing you will need to train for a while. Save up your points untill you find some skill that really neads a boost, or save 20 or so points to put in to alchemy when it becomes available at level 25. Buy any spells you can only get here and at Bearjumper, then gate back.<br><br>You don't have your spell skills maxed, practice them. Perhaps let people know you are buffing and will accept donations, you get a bit of money and your skills get practiced.<br><br>Once your spell skills are maxed, use your shiny new armor to solo some blues to whites (maybe yellows if you really want) to max your melee skills and get some experience. You may level a bit, and get your skills up. Then join a group. At level 10 it's easy to get a group in the dervish camps in North Ro and West Commons. Do that for a while once you get to level 13 or 14 go to the oassis of mar and fight Crocs in a group. After that, It's up to you. I don't know what to do, around level 17 or so the banded armor you have on isn't feeling so invulnerable anymore, and it's time to move on. Ask someone else, because I haven't gotten there yet.<br><br>(currently)<br>Korgish, Justicar of the Tribunal (Shaman)<br>Ayonae Ro<br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
